<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12018f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12018f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12018f"> 18(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ Kilk y Abred / &mdash; y Gwynfyd</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[the prisoner, crazy with lust, fou de d&eacute;sir, rips the druidess from her trance and takes her into the deep cave]</font>: Elle devenait plus belle et presque terrible, ses yeux le transper&ccedil;aient comme deux poignards, quand elle lui r&eacute;v&eacute;lait les trois cercles de l&apos;existence: Annoufen, l&apos;ab&icirc;me, t&eacute;n&eacute;breux d&apos;o&ugrave; sort toute la vie; <mark>Kilk y Abred</mark>, o&ugrave; les &acirc;mes &eacute;migrent de corps en corps; <mark>Kilk y Gwynfyd</mark>, le ciel radieux o&ugrave; r&egrave;gne le bonheur, o&ugrave; l&apos;&acirc;me recouvre sa m&eacute;moire primordiale, o&ugrave; elle retrouve son Awen, son g&eacute;nie primitif. <br><font color="green">[She became more beautiful and almost frightful, her eyes cut through him like two daggers, when she revealed to him the three levels of existence. Annoufen, the abyss, the dark from which all life comes; Kilk y Abred, where the souls go from body to body; Kilk y Gwynfyd, the radiant heaven where happiness reigns, where the soul recovers its primordial memory, where it finds again its Awen, its primitive genius.]</font> <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLL"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1892) 152</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Pictet, <cite>Le myst&egrave;re des bardes</cite>, p. 34: J&apos;ai donc traduit <i>cyclch yr Abred</i>, par <i>cercle de migration</i>, plut&ocirc;t que par <i>cercle du mal</i> avec Turner, ou par <i>cercle du commencement</i> (circle of inchoation) avec Ed. Williams, interpr&eacute;tation que rien ne semble justifier. Quand au <i>cyclch y Gwynfyd</i>, son nom ne donne prise &agrave; aucune incertitude, <i>gwynfyd</i>, (compos&eacute; de <i>gwyn</i>, beau, heureux, et de <i>byd</i>, monde) signifiant, comme <i>gwynfa</i>, un lieu de bonheur, un paradis, et, en g&eacute;n&eacute;ral, f&eacute;licit&eacute;, b&eacute;atitude, etc. <br>[I have therefore translated <i>cylch yr Abred</i> as <i>circle of migration</i> rather than as <i>circle of evil</i>, as Turner did, or as <i>circle of inchoation</i> as Edward Williams did, an interpretation without apparent justification. / As for <i>cylch y Gwynfyd</i>, its name allows for no uncertainty: gwynfud (from gywn, beautiful, happy and byd, world) means, like gwynfa, a happy place, a paradise, and, in general, happiness, beatitude, etc.] </mm> </dd></dl>
